00:02:10,898 --> 00:02:13,492
<i>When your father was a boy like you...</i>

3
00:02:13,834 --> 00:02:15,893
<i>... living with me here in Norway...</i>

4
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:18,665
<i>... I told him about witches, too...</i>

5
00:02:18,839 --> 00:02:21,000
<i>... so that he would always be aware.</i>

6
00:02:22,843 --> 00:02:25,334
<i>The most important thing
youshould know about...</i>

7
00:02:25,412 --> 00:02:27,607
<i>... real witches is this.</i>

8
00:02:27,815 --> 00:02:29,715
<i>Listen very carefully.</i>

9
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:33,642
<i>Real witches dress in ordinary clothes...</i>

10
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:36,188
<i>... and look very much like ordinary women.</i>

11
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:38,390
They live in ordinary houses...

12
00:02:38,459 --> 00:02:41,451
...and they work in ordinary jobs.

13
00:02:45,499 --> 00:02:48,468
Every country in the world has witches.

14
00:02:49,269 --> 00:02:51,362
And there is a leader...

15
00:02:52,272 --> 00:02:54,968
...a high witch of each country.

16
00:02:55,375 --> 00:02:56,740
And the ruler...

17
00:02:57,711 --> 00:02:59,508
...of all the witches...

18
00:02:59,680 --> 00:03:03,116
...is the most evil woman in creation.

19
00:03:03,584 --> 00:03:07,520
The Grand High Witch herself.

20
00:03:12,926 --> 00:03:16,987
Witches spend their time
plotting to kill children.

21
00:03:17,698 --> 00:03:20,462
Stalking the wretched child like a hunter...

22
00:03:20,534 --> 00:03:22,502
...stalks a bird in the forest.

23
00:03:23,237 --> 00:03:24,636
Did they hunt you?

24
00:03:30,978 --> 00:03:32,605
You said it was an accident.

25
00:03:32,679 --> 00:03:35,807
A very unpleasant accident.

26
00:03:36,917 --> 00:03:38,680
When I was younger...

27
00:03:39,453 --> 00:03:42,684
...I traveled the world
in search for the Grand High Witch...

28
00:03:42,756 --> 00:03:44,485
...but I never found her.

29
00:03:44,625 --> 00:03:48,561
I don't really believe
that anyone has ever found her.

30
00:03:49,129 --> 00:03:51,393
If no one's seen the Grand High Witch...

31
00:03:51,465 --> 00:03:53,296
...how are you sure she exists?

32
00:03:53,667 --> 00:03:57,228
Nobody's ever seen the devil,
but we know he exists, don't we?

33
00:03:58,405 --> 00:04:02,000
<i>For all youknow,
a witch might be living next door to you.</i>

34
00:04:03,577 --> 00:04:05,477
<i>When I was little...</i>

35
00:04:05,546 --> 00:04:08,242
<i>... I lived beside a girl called Erica...</i>

36
00:04:08,415 --> 00:04:10,713
<i>... who was taken by a witch.</i>

37
00:04:11,118 --> 00:04:14,212
<i>Erica had very strict parents.</i>

38
00:04:14,922 --> 00:04:17,413
<i>But even that didn't save poor Erica...</i>

39
00:04:17,591 --> 00:04:20,185
<i>... because when a witch chooses a victim...</i>

40
00:04:20,260 --> 00:04:23,127
<i>... there is only one hope of escape:</i>

41
00:04:23,430 --> 00:04:27,491
<i>Knowing everything about them
that I am telling you.</i>

42
00:04:27,868 --> 00:04:29,358
<i>I'm warning you!</i>

43
00:04:30,270 --> 00:04:32,033
Erica, come in.

44
00:04:32,739 --> 00:04:36,675
<i>What makes her dangerous is the fact
that she doesn't look dangerous.</i>

45
00:04:36,977 --> 00:04:40,310
<i>Youcan never be sure
if it's a witch you're looking at...</i>

46
00:04:40,414 --> 00:04:42,109
<i>... or a kind lady.</i>

47
00:04:45,953 --> 00:04:47,250
Erica!

48
00:04:48,889 --> 00:04:50,618
How do you like my new painting?

49
00:04:50,691 --> 00:04:52,283
<i>It's magnifique, Papa.</i>

50
00:04:53,260 --> 00:04:54,625
Go to Larsen's...

51
00:04:55,362 --> 00:04:57,830
...and buy a liter of milk.

52
00:04:58,365 --> 00:04:59,457
Yes, Papa.

53
00:05:03,036 --> 00:05:04,367
Come straight home.

54
00:05:05,939 --> 00:05:08,908
<i>Real witches hate children.</i>

55
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:16,340
Real witches are quite bald.

56
00:05:17,017 --> 00:05:18,882
Although, of course, they wear wigs...

57
00:05:19,252 --> 00:05:20,514
...that itch...

58
00:05:21,188 --> 00:05:23,520
...and cause them scalp rash.

59
00:05:23,790 --> 00:05:25,519
Do you know what scalp rash is?

60
00:05:25,592 --> 00:05:26,490
No.

61
00:05:26,927 --> 00:05:30,829
Itching under the wig.
Must drive them crazy.

62
00:05:31,965 --> 00:05:36,834
They look quite hideous
behind their human facemasks.

63
00:05:37,237 --> 00:05:40,798
<i>They can only be distinguished
from ordinary women...</i>

64
00:05:41,041 --> 00:05:45,637
<i>... if youare sharp enough
to spot the purple tinge to their eyes.</i>

65
00:05:47,314 --> 00:05:50,772
<i>Real witches have no toes.</i>

66
00:05:51,385 --> 00:05:53,717
<i>Their feet have square ends...</i>

67
00:05:53,787 --> 00:05:57,587
<i>... revolting stumps
where their toes should be.</i>

68
00:05:58,025 --> 00:06:01,256
<i>So they never wear pointed
or pretty shoes.</i>

69
00:06:01,328 --> 00:06:04,559
<i>Just plain, sensible shoes.</i>

70
00:06:05,332 --> 00:06:08,096
<i>Remember these things.</i>

71
00:06:09,436 --> 00:06:12,303
<i>Perhaps if Erica had known them...</i>

72
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:29,017
<i>My poor Erica.</i>

73
00:06:29,690 --> 00:06:32,181
<i>For weeks they searched.</i>

74
00:06:32,259 --> 00:06:36,593
<i>But witches don't murder children
with knives or guns.</i>

75
00:06:36,663 --> 00:06:38,824
<i>That's for people who get caught.</i>

76
00:06:38,965 --> 00:06:41,798
<i>And witches never get caught.</i>

77
00:06:43,336 --> 00:06:45,634
<i>They searched for miles around.</i>

78
00:06:46,106 --> 00:06:48,438
<i>Everyone in the town searched...</i>

79
00:06:48,542 --> 00:06:52,376
<i>... but she had completely disappeared.</i>

80
00:06:59,553 --> 00:07:03,046
<i>I was there in Erica's house
six weeks later.</i>

81
00:07:03,191 --> 00:07:04,954
<i>Good day, Frau Larsen.</i>

82
00:07:05,026 --> 00:07:07,051
Come in, Helga. Have some cake.

83
00:07:07,328 --> 00:07:09,853
<i>I was her best friend when it happened.</i>

84
00:07:11,365 --> 00:07:12,889
<i>Then, that day...</i>

85
00:07:13,468 --> 00:07:16,494
<i>... while Erica's mother
was pouring the coffee...</i>

86
00:07:16,904 --> 00:07:19,600
<i>... her father came walking towards us.</i>

87
00:07:20,274 --> 00:07:23,607
<i>It was as though he had seen a ghost.</i>

88
00:07:23,978 --> 00:07:25,605
<i>His face was all twisted up...</i>

89
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:28,444
<i>... as he walked towards the painting
behind me.</i>

90
00:07:29,283 --> 00:07:33,344
<i>There, as if it always had been there...</i>

91
00:07:33,955 --> 00:07:35,354
<i>... was Erica...</i>

92
00:07:35,656 --> 00:07:37,886
<i>... locked in the painting...</i>

93
00:07:37,959 --> 00:07:40,450
<i>... gazing at us.</i>

94
00:07:41,095 --> 00:07:42,824
<i>Papa...</i>

95
00:07:45,199 --> 00:07:48,498
I don't believe it.
You saw her in the painting, Grandma?

96
00:07:48,569 --> 00:07:50,161
Many times.

97
00:07:50,338 --> 00:07:53,739
But the peculiar thing
was that little Erica...

98
00:07:53,808 --> 00:07:57,209
...kept changing her position in the picture.

99
00:07:57,745 --> 00:07:59,679
One day she'd be feeding the ducks.

100
00:07:59,747 --> 00:08:02,375
The next day,
she'd be inside the farmhouse...

101
00:08:02,650 --> 00:08:04,447
...Iooking out of a window.

102
00:08:04,552 --> 00:08:06,816
Did you see her moving in the picture?

103
00:08:06,921 --> 00:08:08,912
Nobody did.

104
00:08:09,257 --> 00:08:11,987
She was always just a figure...

105
00:08:12,393 --> 00:08:14,588
<i>... motionless in the painting.</i>

106
00:08:16,164 --> 00:08:20,032
<i>As the years went by,
Erica grew older, too.</i>

107
00:08:21,702 --> 00:08:24,466
And only five or six years ago...

108
00:08:24,539 --> 00:08:27,303
...the old woman that Erica had become...

109
00:08:27,375 --> 00:08:30,344
...bent and frail in the painting...

110
00:08:30,545 --> 00:08:33,480
...began to disappear.

111
00:08:34,215 --> 00:08:35,443
Until...

112
00:08:36,117 --> 00:08:38,608
...one morning, she was gone.

113
00:08:39,687 --> 00:08:40,949
She died?

114
00:08:41,255 --> 00:08:42,347
Who knows?

115
00:08:42,824 --> 00:08:45,952
Mysterious things go on
in the world of witches.

116
00:08:48,462 --> 00:08:50,191
It's almost 9:00.

117
00:08:50,264 --> 00:08:52,630
Grandma's been telling me
about witches, Mom.

118
00:08:52,700 --> 00:08:55,760
And frightening you before you go to sleep.

119
00:08:56,704 --> 00:08:58,171
Good night, darling.

120
00:08:58,239 --> 00:08:59,467
Everything all right?

121
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:00,837
Very all right.

122
00:09:00,908 --> 00:09:02,398
Go on. Enjoy yourselves.

123
00:09:02,476 --> 00:09:03,738
Good-bye, Mom.

124
00:09:04,679 --> 00:09:05,839
Here you go.

125
00:09:07,048 --> 00:09:09,346
- Good night, son.
- Good night, Dad.

126
00:09:09,417 --> 00:09:11,044
No more stories, okay?

127
00:09:12,119 --> 00:09:13,609
Oh, no.

128
00:09:39,814 --> 00:09:42,009
Come on, just one more story.

129
00:09:42,617 --> 00:09:45,450
All right, one more. But very short.

130
00:09:47,755 --> 00:09:48,983
Witches...

131
00:09:49,390 --> 00:09:51,358
...are very cruel.

132
00:09:51,859 --> 00:09:55,761
They have a highly developed sense
of smell.

133
00:09:56,631 --> 00:09:59,464
A real witch could smell you
across the street...

134
00:09:59,533 --> 00:10:01,364
...on a pitch-black night.

135
00:10:01,669 --> 00:10:03,830
Not me. I just had a shower.

136
00:10:03,938 --> 00:10:05,235
Yes, she could.

137
00:10:05,506 --> 00:10:08,441
The cleaner you are,
the more a witch can smell you.

138
00:10:08,576 --> 00:10:10,168
That doesn't make sense.

139
00:10:10,244 --> 00:10:11,677
Yes, it does.

140
00:10:11,913 --> 00:10:15,041
A dirty child, it's the dirt she smells.

141
00:10:15,116 --> 00:10:17,414
A clean child, it is the child.

142
00:10:21,055 --> 00:10:24,752
I'll never have a shower again,
and I'll have you for an excuse.

143
00:10:25,159 --> 00:10:26,888
Well, just not too often.

144
00:10:26,961 --> 00:10:29,930
Only once a month is probably safe.

145
00:10:30,131 --> 00:10:32,622
So a witch could smell me right now?

146
00:10:32,867 --> 00:10:35,802
To me, you smell of raspberries
and cream...

147
00:10:36,370 --> 00:10:40,204
...but to a witch, you would smell
absolutely disgusting.

148
00:10:40,942 --> 00:10:42,967
What kind of disgusting?

149
00:10:43,311 --> 00:10:45,905
Like dog's droppings.

150
00:10:46,747 --> 00:10:48,180
I don't believe it.

151
00:10:48,249 --> 00:10:49,773
You don't believe it?

152
00:10:50,251 --> 00:10:54,745
What's more, to a witch,
you'd smell of fresh dog's droppings.

153
00:10:54,822 --> 00:10:55,948
That's not true.

154
00:10:56,023 --> 00:10:58,491
There's no point in arguing.
It's a fact of life.

155
00:10:59,226 --> 00:11:03,458
So, if you see a woman holding her nose
as she passes you...

156
00:11:03,698 --> 00:11:05,495
...she could easily be a witch.

157
00:11:06,367 --> 00:11:09,097
And now it is definitely bedtime.

158
00:11:11,339 --> 00:11:12,829
Good night, Grandma.

159
00:11:48,642 --> 00:11:49,609
Mom?

160
00:11:51,245 --> 00:11:52,234
Dad?

161
00:12:27,181 --> 00:12:29,615
<i>Frau Evershim,
could I come in for a minute?</i>

162
00:12:30,251 --> 00:12:32,276
I'm afraid I have some bad news.

163
00:12:32,653 --> 00:12:34,086
Come in.

164
00:12:34,722 --> 00:12:35,814
Wait here.

165
00:12:57,311 --> 00:12:58,801
Come here to me.

166
00:12:59,647 --> 00:13:00,636
Come on.

167
00:13:01,315 --> 00:13:03,044
Let's cuddle up here.

168
00:13:03,250 --> 00:13:05,047
Sit on my lap.

169
00:13:26,207 --> 00:13:28,471
- Shall we bring them to England?
- Yes.

170
00:13:29,210 --> 00:13:31,678
Let's do that. I think they're very good.

171
00:13:32,346 --> 00:13:33,711
I really do.

172
00:13:34,482 --> 00:13:37,815
Quite a talent there,
which I didn't know anything about.

173
00:13:41,255 --> 00:13:42,222
Thanks.

174
00:13:54,201 --> 00:13:56,294
<i>After the accident...</i>

175
00:13:56,504 --> 00:14:00,440
<i>... I didn't take Luke
back to America right away.</i>

176
00:14:00,908 --> 00:14:03,206
<i>We went to England where I had a house.</i>

177
00:14:03,377 --> 00:14:07,177
<i>He started at the school his parents
had chosen for him before they...</i>

178
00:14:07,248 --> 00:14:09,580
- Bald?
- That's why they wear wigs.

179
00:14:09,683 --> 00:14:12,015
<i>Before they came to me on their vacation.</i>

180
00:14:12,086 --> 00:14:13,348
They itch and scratch a lot.

181
00:14:13,420 --> 00:14:15,820
I saw a woman yesterday with purple eyes.

182
00:14:34,008 --> 00:14:35,373
Hello, young man.

183
00:14:36,310 --> 00:14:38,744
What a magnificent tree house.

184
00:14:39,246 --> 00:14:40,975
Did you build it yourself?

185
00:14:41,148 --> 00:14:42,615
My dad and I did.

186
00:14:45,019 --> 00:14:47,010
I've got something for you here.

187
00:14:48,189 --> 00:14:50,350
Something I think you'll like.

188
00:14:51,258 --> 00:14:53,089
- Jump down and I'll show you.
- No.

189
00:14:53,160 --> 00:14:55,492
- What?
- No, thank you very much.

190
00:14:55,629 --> 00:14:57,893
It's worth a lot of money.

191
00:14:58,566 --> 00:14:59,999
This is private property.

192
00:15:00,067 --> 00:15:01,796
There's nothing to be frightened of.

193
00:15:01,869 --> 00:15:03,962
I just wanted to give you this.

194
00:15:05,472 --> 00:15:08,873
I found him on my walk.
He's quite harmless.

195
00:15:10,811 --> 00:15:11,675
See?

196
00:15:12,813 --> 00:15:14,781
Little boys love snakes.

197
00:15:16,984 --> 00:15:18,576
Here, he's yours.

198
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:21,245
Grandma! Grandma!

199
00:15:21,355 --> 00:15:24,722
I'll leave him here if you like.
Then you can come down and get him.

200
00:15:25,993 --> 00:15:28,120
They wriggle away quite quickly...

201
00:15:29,129 --> 00:15:31,893
...unless you tell them not to.

202
00:15:36,670 --> 00:15:38,968
Grandma!

203
00:15:40,774 --> 00:15:43,072
Perhaps you'd like some chocolate.

204
00:15:43,777 --> 00:15:46,541
Grandma!

205
00:15:46,614 --> 00:15:49,242
She can't hear you.

206
00:15:50,851 --> 00:15:52,318
What's your name?

207
00:15:52,453 --> 00:15:53,442
Is it...

208
00:15:55,122 --> 00:15:56,180
...Luke?

209
00:15:57,124 --> 00:15:58,250
Thought so.

210
00:15:58,626 --> 00:16:00,617
Here you are, Luke.

211
00:16:01,161 --> 00:16:05,063
A big bar of chocolate.

212
00:16:05,633 --> 00:16:07,362
- Lf you...
- Luke.

213
00:16:08,636 --> 00:16:10,297
Luke, it's dinnertime.

214
00:16:18,912 --> 00:16:21,005
Luke, dinnertime.

215
00:16:27,821 --> 00:16:30,722
- Did you see her?
- Yes.

216
00:16:31,425 --> 00:16:34,087
I think she was a witch.
Gloves, purple eyes.

217
00:16:34,161 --> 00:16:36,061
She wanted me to climb down and...

218
00:16:36,130 --> 00:16:38,257
...she hypnotized a snake
she wanted to give me.

219
00:16:38,332 --> 00:16:39,800
A real one?

220
00:16:39,934 --> 00:16:41,458
A real snake, yes!

221
00:16:45,473 --> 00:16:46,565
I swear.

222
00:16:49,210 --> 00:16:50,472
I believe you.

223
00:17:04,059 --> 00:17:05,856
Close your eyes. No cheating.

224
00:17:05,927 --> 00:17:08,054
To your chair. There we are.

225
00:17:08,129 --> 00:17:10,723
"Happy birthday to you

226
00:17:10,932 --> 00:17:13,332
"Happy birthday to you

227
00:17:13,501 --> 00:17:16,368
"Happy birthday, dear Luke

228
00:17:16,504 --> 00:17:18,267
"Happy birthday to you"

229
00:17:18,340 --> 00:17:19,568
There!

230
00:17:19,674 --> 00:17:21,335
They're great!

231
00:17:22,143 --> 00:17:23,940
I'll build them a whole circus...

232
00:17:24,012 --> 00:17:26,913
...teach them tricks
and acrobatics and stuff.

233
00:17:27,082 --> 00:17:29,414
It must be so neat being a mouse.

234
00:17:29,484 --> 00:17:33,352
<i>Just play all day and eat,
and then play some more.</i>

235
00:17:33,722 --> 00:17:36,384
I'll rig up a whole room with...

236
00:17:37,959 --> 00:17:39,517
Grandma!

237
00:17:41,096 --> 00:17:42,393
Grandma!

238
00:17:45,300 --> 00:17:48,565
Your granny has a mild case of diabetes.

239
00:17:48,670 --> 00:17:50,399
It's nothing to worry about.

240
00:17:50,472 --> 00:17:53,839
Have a good rest,
and soon you'll be as right as rain.

241
00:17:53,908 --> 00:17:55,273
You'll be better.

242
00:17:55,610 --> 00:17:57,737
I'm putting you on a sugar-free diet.

243
00:17:57,812 --> 00:18:01,111
No cakes, candies, or sugar at all.

244
00:18:01,983 --> 00:18:04,076
Those cigars won't do you any good.

245
00:18:04,152 --> 00:18:04,811
See?

246
00:18:04,886 --> 00:18:06,786
There are some more pills to take.

247
00:18:06,988 --> 00:18:09,422
With that and a good holiday
by the seaside...

248
00:18:09,557 --> 00:18:11,286
...you'll be good as new.

249
00:18:11,693 --> 00:18:14,856
Come on, leave your granny to rest.

250
00:18:14,963 --> 00:18:18,194
Perhaps you can bring her breakfast in bed
in the morning.

251
00:18:18,800 --> 00:18:22,201
By tomorrow afternoon,
you can boss her around like before.

252
00:18:22,270 --> 00:18:24,261
- Bye-bye, Mrs. Evershim.
- Bye-bye.

253
00:18:24,339 --> 00:18:26,170
See you in a couple of days.

254
00:18:27,208 --> 00:18:28,835
- Can you find your way?
- Yes.

255
00:18:28,910 --> 00:18:31,902
How come doctors speak to everybody
like they're babies?

256
00:18:31,980 --> 00:18:33,208
I know.

257
00:18:34,382 --> 00:18:36,942
I'm sorry for spoiling your birthday...

258
00:18:37,118 --> 00:18:39,109
...and for giving you a fright.

259
00:18:40,188 --> 00:18:43,123
Is it all right if I play
with William and Mary now?

260
00:18:43,224 --> 00:18:44,521
Yes, of course.

261
00:19:02,877 --> 00:19:05,277
Listen, Mary Mouse,
when Grandma gets better...

262
00:19:05,346 --> 00:19:08,179
...we're going with her to a hotel
by the ocean.

263
00:19:08,316 --> 00:19:10,307
You've never been to the ocean.

264
00:19:10,585 --> 00:19:11,609
I'll tell you, it's big.

265
00:19:22,297 --> 00:19:24,162
Look at the hotel, Grandma.

266
00:19:24,432 --> 00:19:25,865
It's not half bad.

267
00:19:39,047 --> 00:19:40,844
- Welcome, madam.
- Thank you.

268
00:19:40,915 --> 00:19:42,883
Think it'll be a nice day, yes?

269
00:19:43,117 --> 00:19:44,641
Can you manage, Luke?

270
00:20:04,739 --> 00:20:06,536
Come on, Luke. There we go.

271
00:20:11,913 --> 00:20:14,473
Welcome to the Excelsior! Nicola Cole.

272
00:20:14,549 --> 00:20:16,107
I've looked forward to meeting you.

273
00:20:16,184 --> 00:20:17,549
You look marvelous.

274
00:20:17,619 --> 00:20:19,780
Wish I could say the same for you.

275
00:20:21,289 --> 00:20:24,019
Miss Ernst. I am the owner of the hotel.

276
00:20:25,460 --> 00:20:27,519
We're very happy to have you here.

277
00:20:27,595 --> 00:20:29,859
Delighted. Should I sign or something?

278
00:20:30,031 --> 00:20:31,589
This is my secretary.

279
00:20:32,433 --> 00:20:34,162
Yes. How are you?

280
00:20:34,402 --> 00:20:35,767
Ladies.

281
00:20:36,571 --> 00:20:38,334
- Ina Clay Beckman.
- Indeed.

282
00:20:38,406 --> 00:20:39,998
<i>Julia Whitman.</i>

283
00:20:40,074 --> 00:20:42,804
<i>Julia. Yes. Where are you from?</i>

284
00:20:42,877 --> 00:20:44,174
Darlington.

285
00:20:44,779 --> 00:20:47,043
- Lois Leffour, from Southampton.
- Lois.

286
00:20:59,661 --> 00:21:02,027
In there, that must be where you sleep.

287
00:21:03,631 --> 00:21:06,566
The carpetbag on the bed, please.

288
00:21:07,168 --> 00:21:10,763
I'll have a wash and brush-up
while you explore the place.

289
00:21:10,972 --> 00:21:13,566
Then we shall have tea together...

290
00:21:13,841 --> 00:21:16,275
...and you'll show me around, yes?

291
00:21:16,344 --> 00:21:17,368
Thank you.

292
00:21:17,445 --> 00:21:18,844
Don't lock me out.

293
00:21:18,913 --> 00:21:20,778
I promise I won't.

294
00:21:31,259 --> 00:21:33,284
You look wonderful, Miss Ernst.

295
00:21:33,361 --> 00:21:36,296
We are looking forward to this afternoon.

296
00:22:15,703 --> 00:22:17,170
What are you doing?

297
00:22:17,939 --> 00:22:20,737
The raisins are all around the edge
of these cakes.

298
00:22:20,808 --> 00:22:22,298
They're really good.

299
00:22:22,543 --> 00:22:23,532
Thanks.

300
00:22:25,647 --> 00:22:26,944
My name's Luke.

301
00:22:28,783 --> 00:22:30,478
Bruno Jenkins.

302
00:22:30,885 --> 00:22:33,376
The cucumber sandwiches
are all right, too...

303
00:22:33,454 --> 00:22:36,389
...except when they use margarine
instead of butter.

304
00:22:36,791 --> 00:22:39,021
How much pocket money do you get?

305
00:22:39,127 --> 00:22:42,290
My dad's rich, but he's very tight.

306
00:22:42,463 --> 00:22:44,021
We've got three cars.

307
00:22:44,098 --> 00:22:45,258
Hello, boys.

308
00:22:45,400 --> 00:22:48,096
I hope there's butter
in the sandwiches today.

309
00:22:48,169 --> 00:22:50,763
I really do hate margarine.

310
00:22:51,639 --> 00:22:54,039
You've got those excellent cakes again.

311
00:22:54,108 --> 00:22:55,905
<i>There should be 14 of the...</i>

312
00:22:57,645 --> 00:22:59,010
Mr. Stringer!

313
00:23:01,516 --> 00:23:04,974
- What happened?
- I went to make the bed. They were there.

314
00:23:05,053 --> 00:23:07,851
- What?
- White and disgusting.

315
00:23:09,290 --> 00:23:10,917
Calm down.

316
00:23:23,905 --> 00:23:25,998
Is this your room?

317
00:23:26,307 --> 00:23:27,433
Yes.

318
00:23:29,110 --> 00:23:32,807
I'm sorry, madam,
but I cannot permit mice in my hotel.

319
00:23:32,880 --> 00:23:35,041
How dare you say that
when your rotten hotel...

320
00:23:35,116 --> 00:23:37,050
...is full of rats anyway?

321
00:23:37,118 --> 00:23:38,346
Rats?

322
00:23:39,020 --> 00:23:40,783
There are no rats in this hotel.

323
00:23:40,855 --> 00:23:44,518
I saw one this morning running
along the corridor into the kitchen.

324
00:23:44,959 --> 00:23:49,419
Madam, you only arrived in the hotel
this afternoon.

325
00:23:49,564 --> 00:23:50,895
Morning, afternoon.

326
00:23:50,965 --> 00:23:53,229
I saw a rat in your hotel...

327
00:23:53,334 --> 00:23:55,598
...and if matters do not improve...

328
00:23:55,670 --> 00:23:59,128
...I'll have to report you
to the public health authorities.

329
00:24:01,409 --> 00:24:03,673
Look, madam, I'm not prepared...

330
00:24:03,745 --> 00:24:07,340
The cakes in the lounge are nibbled
all around the edges. I can show you.

331
00:24:07,415 --> 00:24:08,677
If you're not careful...

332
00:24:08,750 --> 00:24:11,514
...the health people
will order the whole hotel closed...

333
00:24:11,586 --> 00:24:14,282
...before everyone gets typhoid fever.

334
00:24:14,355 --> 00:24:16,255
You can't be serious, madam.

335
00:24:16,390 --> 00:24:18,756
I've never been more serious in my life.

336
00:24:18,860 --> 00:24:22,956
Now, will you or will you not
let my grandchild...

337
00:24:23,030 --> 00:24:26,989
...keep his hygienic
and perfectly harmless pet mice?

338
00:24:34,008 --> 00:24:37,034
If they are kept in the cage,
and only in this room.

339
00:24:37,111 --> 00:24:38,772
Nowhere else in the hotel!

340
00:24:38,846 --> 00:24:40,006
Agreed.

341
00:24:40,915 --> 00:24:42,007
Very well.

342
00:24:50,958 --> 00:24:52,050
Grandma...

343
00:24:52,126 --> 00:24:54,720
...I can't train my mice if they're in a cage.

344
00:24:54,796 --> 00:24:57,230
Nibbled cakes, indeed.

345
00:24:57,431 --> 00:25:01,128
There were,
only it was a boy called Bruno Jenkins.

346
00:25:01,269 --> 00:25:05,433
I'm teaching William and Mary
how to be tightrope walkers.

347
00:25:05,540 --> 00:25:08,100
I brought the circus I'm building with me.

348
00:25:08,176 --> 00:25:09,575
Good. Show me.

349
00:25:13,247 --> 00:25:14,305
Let's see.

350
00:25:14,382 --> 00:25:16,873
Look. I'm planning them a major house.

351
00:25:16,951 --> 00:25:20,978
Ramp ways here, a bathtub.
This elevator's pretty neat.

352
00:25:21,055 --> 00:25:25,492
You really did this yourself?
It's good. I'm impressed.

353
00:25:25,626 --> 00:25:27,218
You must train your mice...

354
00:25:27,295 --> 00:25:30,128
...but you mustn't get caught
or do it in here...

355
00:25:30,198 --> 00:25:32,996
...because if that hysterical maid
comes back...

356
00:25:34,836 --> 00:25:36,326
Now it's teatime.

357
00:25:36,404 --> 00:25:40,033
I just love English hotel teas.

358
00:25:40,141 --> 00:25:42,666
Cream cakes and shortbread and...

359
00:25:42,810 --> 00:25:44,004
No, Grandma.

360
00:25:44,078 --> 00:25:45,875
No cream cakes.

361
00:25:45,980 --> 00:25:48,380
And no shortbread, either.
It's full of sugar.

362
00:25:48,449 --> 00:25:51,145
I shall end up eating the same diet
as your mice.

363
00:25:51,853 --> 00:25:54,879
That's the trouble with this country:
A queue for everything.

364
00:25:55,089 --> 00:25:57,216
They wouldn't think to have
two tea trolleys.

365
00:25:57,291 --> 00:26:00,158
No, that'd be too convenient
for the paying guests.

366
00:26:00,428 --> 00:26:03,363
They'll want two lumps of ice
in their whiskey next.

367
00:26:03,598 --> 00:26:06,431
They'd queue for their own funerals
if they could.

368
00:26:07,001 --> 00:26:09,697
I know that woman from somewhere...

369
00:26:10,271 --> 00:26:13,069
...but I can't for the life of me
remember where.

370
00:26:15,009 --> 00:26:17,535
Her face is so familiar.

371
00:26:18,780 --> 00:26:20,077
Which one?

372
00:26:20,282 --> 00:26:22,045
My memory's going.

373
00:26:22,117 --> 00:26:24,517
But it's as if I met her before.

374
00:26:25,053 --> 00:26:27,146
She's probably on TV or something.

375
00:26:27,856 --> 00:26:29,847
Cucumber sandwiches.

376
00:26:32,794 --> 00:26:34,591
Fish paste.

377
00:26:34,663 --> 00:26:36,460
You got the wrong one.

378
00:26:37,666 --> 00:26:39,861
Oh, no. Sugar.

379
00:26:40,102 --> 00:26:42,036
Sugar can kill you.

380
00:26:42,137 --> 00:26:45,129
I know, but it was very little.

381
00:26:46,108 --> 00:26:48,872
Something very odd is going on.

382
00:26:48,944 --> 00:26:50,377
Are you listening to me?

383
00:26:50,445 --> 00:26:53,539
You'll have some fresh air
if I have to take you out by your ear.

384
00:26:54,383 --> 00:26:57,580
We didn't come here for you to sit eating
and watch telly all day.

385
00:26:57,920 --> 00:27:00,855
All the other boys are out there
playing in the water.

386
00:27:00,923 --> 00:27:02,356
Pick up your knife.

387
00:27:02,424 --> 00:27:04,324
You're just like your father.

388
00:27:10,432 --> 00:27:12,024
Good afternoon, madam.

389
00:27:14,503 --> 00:27:15,333
Go on.

390
00:27:15,404 --> 00:27:17,304
Are you sure you're all right?

391
00:27:18,106 --> 00:27:19,334
Fine, fine.

392
00:27:20,609 --> 00:27:22,600
What are you going to do now?

393
00:27:22,678 --> 00:27:25,704
I'm gonna take William and Mary
and explore this place.

394
00:27:25,781 --> 00:27:28,579
<i>Just don't get into trouble, will you?</i>

395
00:27:28,650 --> 00:27:29,617
I won't.

396
00:27:29,685 --> 00:27:30,777
Come on.

397
00:27:35,190 --> 00:27:37,181
Excuse me, please.

398
00:27:40,862 --> 00:27:42,261
That's fine.

399
00:27:44,032 --> 00:27:45,795
Carry on with the rest of them.

400
00:27:45,867 --> 00:27:47,858
No. In the kitchen.

401
00:28:40,889 --> 00:28:42,049
Wait there.

402
00:28:58,273 --> 00:29:00,138
Great. Now do it again.

403
00:29:02,077 --> 00:29:03,339
Come on.

404
00:29:03,412 --> 00:29:06,643
I'm sure your delegates
will be comfortable in here.

405
00:29:06,915 --> 00:29:09,076
If there's anything we can do...

406
00:29:09,217 --> 00:29:11,117
Come on, Nicola, down the front!

407
00:29:13,321 --> 00:29:16,415
Drinks will be served on the terrace after...

408
00:29:17,325 --> 00:29:19,156
...you've concluded your meeting.

409
00:29:19,227 --> 00:29:21,422
Skies are clearing, I'm glad to say.

410
00:29:21,997 --> 00:29:23,055
Sit down.

411
00:29:23,131 --> 00:29:25,725
We've prepared a fine meal for you tonight.

412
00:29:25,801 --> 00:29:27,666
The chef's special soup...

413
00:29:35,677 --> 00:29:37,076
Look at her eyes.

414
00:29:40,482 --> 00:29:41,949
I'll leave you to business.

415
00:29:42,017 --> 00:29:43,382
Fine. Thank you.

416
00:29:44,219 --> 00:29:46,016
Everybody sitting?

417
00:29:46,388 --> 00:29:47,821
Up front, sit down!

418
00:29:47,889 --> 00:29:50,289
Not yet!

419
00:29:50,725 --> 00:29:51,953
We've got to get out of here.

420
00:29:52,027 --> 00:29:53,324
Come along, ladies.

421
00:29:53,395 --> 00:29:55,989
The sooner you're ready,
the sooner we can start.

422
00:29:57,999 --> 00:30:00,263
Thank you for letting me stay.

423
00:30:00,335 --> 00:30:03,065
- That's all right, Elsie.
- I'll lock up.

424
00:30:03,138 --> 00:30:04,162
- Good.
- Good.

425
00:30:04,239 --> 00:30:05,604
Then we'll begin.

426
00:30:35,337 --> 00:30:38,306
You may remove your shoes.

427
00:30:42,377 --> 00:30:44,777
You may remove your wigs.

428
00:30:46,114 --> 00:30:49,106
The doors, are they locked and bolted?

429
00:30:50,418 --> 00:30:52,477
Locked and bolted, Your Grandness.

430
00:30:52,554 --> 00:30:53,987
Good. Help me.

431
00:31:17,979 --> 00:31:20,777
Witches of England...

432
00:31:22,417 --> 00:31:24,942
...you're a disgrace!

433
00:31:26,188 --> 00:31:28,019
Miserable witches...

434
00:31:29,090 --> 00:31:32,526
...you are good-for-nothing worms!

435
00:31:33,762 --> 00:31:35,662
Everywhere I look...

436
00:31:38,500 --> 00:31:40,991
...I see the repulsive sight...

437
00:31:41,336 --> 00:31:42,894
...of hundreds...

438
00:31:43,939 --> 00:31:45,804
...thousands...

439
00:31:46,441 --> 00:31:48,466
...of revolting little children.

440
00:31:51,479 --> 00:31:52,844
I ask you:

441
00:31:54,082 --> 00:31:55,071
Why?

442
00:31:58,353 --> 00:32:00,981
One child a week is no good to me.

443
00:32:01,923 --> 00:32:03,288
We will do better.

444
00:32:03,458 --> 00:32:05,426
We will do much better.

445
00:32:06,127 --> 00:32:09,153
Better is no good, either!

446
00:32:10,565 --> 00:32:14,729
I demand maximum results.

447
00:32:15,770 --> 00:32:16,998
So...

448
00:32:18,173 --> 00:32:20,698
...here are my orders.

449
00:32:22,077 --> 00:32:24,136
My orders are...

450
00:32:25,046 --> 00:32:26,946
...that every child...

451
00:32:27,816 --> 00:32:29,181
...in England...

452
00:32:29,918 --> 00:32:31,909
...shall be rubbed out.

453
00:32:32,621 --> 00:32:33,986
Destroyed!

454
00:32:35,457 --> 00:32:38,153
Every single child eliminated!

455
00:32:39,794 --> 00:32:43,059
Do I make myself clear?

456
00:32:47,602 --> 00:32:49,900
We can't possibly wipe out all of them.

457
00:32:51,740 --> 00:32:52,900
Who spoke?

458
00:32:55,744 --> 00:32:57,974
Who dares to argue with me?

459
00:33:01,483 --> 00:33:02,916
It was you?

460
00:33:03,385 --> 00:33:04,852
I didn't mean to argue.

461
00:33:04,919 --> 00:33:07,752
You dare to argue with me?

462
00:33:07,856 --> 00:33:10,188
No, honestly. It just was a...

463
00:33:10,692 --> 00:33:13,923
A stupid witch who answers back...

464
00:33:14,129 --> 00:33:16,689
...must burn until her bones are black!

465
00:33:16,798 --> 00:33:17,787
No.

466
00:33:17,899 --> 00:33:19,457
A foolish witch...

467
00:33:20,168 --> 00:33:21,692
...without a brain...

468
00:33:22,304 --> 00:33:24,966
...must sizzle into fiery flame!

469
00:33:25,840 --> 00:33:27,034
A witch...

470
00:33:27,309 --> 00:33:29,834
...who dares to say I'm wrong...

471
00:33:31,146 --> 00:33:33,614
...will not be with us...

472
00:33:33,882 --> 00:33:35,110
...very long!

473
00:33:38,420 --> 00:33:39,944
What the devil?

474
00:33:57,072 --> 00:34:01,805
I hope nobody else
is going to make me cross today.

475
00:34:05,613 --> 00:34:07,808
Now, this is my plan.

476
00:34:09,117 --> 00:34:10,379
Each of you...

477
00:34:10,952 --> 00:34:12,977
...will go back to your homes...

478
00:34:13,421 --> 00:34:16,322
...and resign from your jobs.

479
00:34:17,125 --> 00:34:18,319
Give notice.

480
00:34:18,793 --> 00:34:19,987
Retire.

481
00:34:21,696 --> 00:34:24,597
You will then buy,
with the money I give you...

482
00:34:25,567 --> 00:34:26,898
...sweet shops.

483
00:34:27,402 --> 00:34:28,664
Candy stores.

484
00:34:29,738 --> 00:34:33,970
The best and most respectable
sweet shops in England.

485
00:34:40,715 --> 00:34:44,378
Upstairs I have a trunkload
of this English money...

486
00:34:44,686 --> 00:34:46,950
...so you'll be able to offer three...

487
00:34:47,021 --> 00:34:50,047
...maybe four times
what these shops are worth.

488
00:34:50,125 --> 00:34:51,114
Go.

489
00:34:54,162 --> 00:34:55,925
On a certain day...

490
00:34:56,030 --> 00:34:58,498
...when all our plans are prepared...

491
00:34:58,633 --> 00:35:03,263
...you'll announce a great gala opening...

492
00:35:03,471 --> 00:35:07,805
...with free sweets, candies,
and chocolates for every child.

493
00:35:08,476 --> 00:35:09,966
Poison sweets.

494
00:35:10,178 --> 00:35:12,908
We'll wipe them out like weasels.

495
00:35:13,681 --> 00:35:15,615
- Who spoke?
- She did!

496
00:35:17,252 --> 00:35:18,583
It's brilliant.

497
00:35:19,287 --> 00:35:20,254
Poison?

498
00:35:21,423 --> 00:35:23,891
And you don't mind getting caught?

499
00:35:24,793 --> 00:35:26,590
Exposed?

500
00:35:26,928 --> 00:35:28,862
Vilified?

501
00:35:28,930 --> 00:35:30,227
I just thought...

502
00:35:30,298 --> 00:35:32,129
Spineless bumpkin!

503
00:35:32,767 --> 00:35:34,997
You blithering bogvumper!

504
00:35:35,570 --> 00:35:38,505
No wonder England is swarming with...

505
00:35:49,851 --> 00:35:52,877
Everything you sell that day...

506
00:35:54,189 --> 00:35:56,021
...will have been treated...

507
00:35:56,392 --> 00:35:58,383
...with my very latest...

508
00:35:59,195 --> 00:36:02,494
...and very greatest magic formula.

509
00:36:03,966 --> 00:36:07,527
Witches work only with magic!

510
00:36:08,737 --> 00:36:10,102
Wait. Come here.

511
00:36:11,073 --> 00:36:13,303
<i>Formula 86.</i>

512
00:36:14,043 --> 00:36:15,567
My greatest triumph.

513
00:36:17,179 --> 00:36:18,373
A work of...

514
00:36:19,682 --> 00:36:21,013
...genius.

515
00:36:22,518 --> 00:36:24,918
<i>Formula 86!</i>

516
00:36:25,821 --> 00:36:27,152
In this bottle...

517
00:36:27,656 --> 00:36:30,750
...500 doses...

518
00:36:30,826 --> 00:36:32,657
...with a delay mechanism...

519
00:36:32,728 --> 00:36:35,856
...that prevents it from working
until two hours...

520
00:36:36,098 --> 00:36:37,895
...after it has been taken.

521
00:36:40,903 --> 00:36:42,302
What does it do...

522
00:36:42,738 --> 00:36:44,365
...genius one?

523
00:36:52,948 --> 00:36:54,074
One dose...

524
00:36:54,783 --> 00:36:57,047
...and the time works to the second.

525
00:36:58,220 --> 00:37:00,620
But more than five doses...

526
00:37:00,923 --> 00:37:02,618
...breaks the delay barrier...

